gov.nasa.arc.mct.services.component
Class ViewInfo

java.lang.Object
  gov.nasa.arc.mct.services.component.ViewInfo

public class ViewInfo
extends java.lang.Object

The ViewInfo class describes metadata about a view. This class is used to create new view instances.

ViewInfo

public ViewInfo(java.lang.Class<? extends View> aViewClass,
                java.lang.String name,
                java.lang.String aType,
                ViewType viewType)
         throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
Creates a new instance of ViewInfo. This constructor should only be used when attempting to provide backward compatibility for views which have already been serialized. The serialized mapping uses the type to determine how to map the state to a view type.

Parameters:
aViewClass - representing a view.
name - human readable name of the view
aType - representing the type used when serializing the view state. The type must be unique across all serialized view states so the default type used is the fully qualified class name.
viewType - for this view
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the view type is null or the class doesn't have the right type of constructor

                javax.swing.ImageIcon icon,
                javax.swing.ImageIcon selectedIcon)
         throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
Creates a new instance of ViewInfo. This constructor should only be used when attempting to provide backward compatibility for views which have already been serialized. The serialized mapping uses the type to determine how to map the state to a view type.

Parameters:
aViewClass - representing a view.
name - human readable name of the view
aType - representing the type used when serializing the view state. The type must be unique across all serialized view states so the default type used is the fully qualified class name.
viewType - for this view
icon - to be placed in a button for this view. This icon is typically used for button showing in the inspector.
selectedIcon - icon to be placed in a button for this view. This icon is typically used for button showing in the inspector when the button is selected.
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the view type is null or the class doesn't have the right type of constructor
